explanation: NOT_FOUND_ERROR: Need the actual declaration/definition (macro or variable) to determine whether the underlying object is const-qualified (e.g. const char[] or const char *). The call casts it to (const void *); MISRA prefers the object itself be declared const where possible rather than rely on casts. MHD_create_response_from_buffer_static (prototype): The const-qualification of its buffer parameter is critical. If this API accepts a non-const void * (or stores a non-const pointer internally) that forces callers to supply non-const pointers; if it accepts const void * then the call is const-correct. Knowing the exact parameter type determines whether the cast and usage comply with MISRA. MHD_create_response_from_buffer_with_free_callback_cls (prototype): The static wrapper delegates to this underlying function. Its parameter types and any free-callback or ownership semantics determine whether the buffer pointer must be non-const (e.g. if the implementation will free or modify the buffer), which affects whether the buffer can/should be declared const. MHD_add_response_header (prototype): We must know the const-qualification of the header-name and header-value parameters. The function is called with mime (const char *) and a header macro; if the function expects non-const char * this may force dropping constness. MHD_HTTP_HEADER_CONTENT_ENCODING: The header-name macro/constant's type (string literal, char[], const char *) is required to know whether the header argument is const-qualified at the definition site. struct MHD_Response (definition): Knowing whether response objects and their header storage accept const-qualified pointers or will mutate stored pointers helps determine whether passing const data (like NOT_FOUND_ERROR or mime) is appropriate or requires non-const storage/copies. These symbols together let an analyzer determine whether pointer types are correctly const-qualified in the call chain (and whether casts hide constness issues) to judge compliance with the MISRA rule.
